  urldate = {2025-02-27},
  abstract = {We explicitly construct nondegenerate braided \$\textbackslash mathbb\{Z\}\_2\$-crossed tensor categories of the form \$\textbackslash operatorname\{Vect\}\_\textbackslash Gamma\textbackslash oplus\textbackslash operatorname\{Vect\}\_\{\textbackslash Gamma/2\textbackslash Gamma\}\$. They are \$\textbackslash mathbb\{Z\}\_2\$-crossed extensions, in the sense of arXiv:0909.3140, of the braided tensor category \$\textbackslash operatorname\{Vect\}\_\textbackslash Gamma\$ with \$\textbackslash mathbb\{Z\}\_2\$-action given by \$-\textbackslash mathrm\{id\}\$ on the finite, abelian group \$\textbackslash Gamma\$. Thus, we obtain generalisations of the Tambara-Yamagami categories, where now the abelian group \$\textbackslash Gamma\$ may have even order and the nontrivial sector \$\textbackslash operatorname\{Vect\}\_\{\textbackslash Gamma/2\textbackslash Gamma\}\$ more than one simple object. The idea for this construction comes from a physically motivated approach in arXiv:2409.16357 to construct \$\textbackslash mathbb\{Z\}\_2\$-crossed extensions of \$\textbackslash operatorname\{Vect\}\_\textbackslash Gamma\$ for any \$\textbackslash Gamma\$ from an infinite Tambara-Yamagami category \$\textbackslash operatorname\{Vect\}\_\{\textbackslash mathbb\{R\}\textasciicircum d\}\textbackslash oplus\textbackslash operatorname\{Vect\}\$, which itself is not fully rigorously defined, and then using condensation from \$\textbackslash operatorname\{Vect\}\_\{\textbackslash mathbb\{R\}\textasciicircum d\}\$ to \$\textbackslash operatorname\{Vect\}\_\textbackslash Gamma\$, which we prove commutes with crossed extensions. The \$\textbackslash mathbb\{Z\}\_2\$-equivariantisation of \$\textbackslash operatorname\{Vect\}\_\textbackslash Gamma\textbackslash oplus\textbackslash operatorname\{Vect\}\_\{\textbackslash Gamma/2\textbackslash Gamma\}\$ yields new modular tensor categories, which correspond to the orbifold of an arbitrary lattice vertex operator algebra under a lift of \$-\textbackslash mathrm\{id\}\$, as discussed in arXiv:2409.16357.},
